-- Raw Materials Fall, Led by Gold, Silver: Commodities at Close
-- B y   P a t r i c k   M c K i e r n a n
-- 2013-04-12T22:02:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-12/raw-materials-fall-led-by-gold-silver-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot
Index of 24  raw materials  fell 1.3 percent to settle at 623.16
at 3:42 p.m. New York time, led by precious metals. The broad
measure dropped to the lowest since July.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  gauge  of 26 prices dropped 1.2
percent to 1,492.25.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold tumbled to the lowest since July 2011, slumping into a
 bear market , on signs that investors are favoring the dollar and
equities as the global economy recovers.  Today, the greenback rose as much as 0.5 percent against
the euro, and the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index of shares climbed
to a record yesterday. Cyprus may sell gold holdings to cover
possible losses from emergency loans.  On the Comex in New York, gold futures for June delivery
plunged 4.1 percent to $1,501.40 an ounce. The metal dropped 21
percent from a record settlement of $1,891.90 in August 2011,
meeting the common definition of a bear market.  Silver futures for May delivery dropped 4.9 percent to
$26.331 an ounce, the biggest decline since June.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , platinum futures for
July delivery slid 2.6 percent to $1,495.90 an ounce.  Palladium futures for June delivery fell 3.3 percent to
$709.10 an ounce.  BASE METALS  Zinc fell, capping the longest run of weekly declines in at
least two decades, on concern that economies from the U.S. to
 China  are struggling to maintain economic expansion.  On the London Metal Exchange, zinc for delivery in three
months declined 2 percent to $1,875 a metric ton. The price
dropped for the ninth straight week, the longest slump since at
least January 1989.  Copper, aluminum, nickel, lead and tin also dropped. A
gauge of the six LME metals tumbled the most in a year.  On the Comex, copper futures for May delivery fell 2.5
percent to $3.348 a pound.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil fell to a one-month low after U.S. retail sales
and  consumer confidence  declined, signaling lower fuel demand.  On the Nymex, oil futures for May delivery declined 2.4
percent to $91.29 a barrel, the lowest settlement since March 6.  Brent for May settlement fell 1.1 percent to $103.11 a
barrel on the London-based ICE Futures  Europe  exchange, the
lowest closing price since July 13.  Total SA failed to buy more North Sea Forties crude, having
bought nine cargoes since March 27, even as it bid at a higher
level than yesterday’s trade.  The  oil company , Europe’s third-largest, chartered a
supertanker to transport North Sea Forties crude to  South Korea .
That increased total shipments to the country this year to 13
million barrels, according to a shipbroker report.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline fell to a 12-week low on concern that U.S. and
European economies are weakening, reducing fuel demand at the
same time that refineries increase output.  On the Nymex, gasoline futures for May delivery dropped 1
percent $2.8018 a gallon, the lowest settlement since Jan. 18.  Ultra low-sulfur-diesel futures for May delivery declined
0.9 percent to $2.8718 a gallon, the lowest settlement in three
weeks.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas climbed, capping the longest run of weekly
gains since October 2009, on speculation that cold weather would
widen a U.S. supply deficit.  On the Nymex, gas futures for May delivery rose 2 percent
to settle $4.222 per million British thermal units, the highest
settlement since July 28, 2011. The price advanced for the
eighth straight week.  U.K. gas for same-day delivery rose as much as 3.6 percent
to 72 pence a therm and traded at 71.6 pence at 3:22 p.m. London
time, broker data show.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cotton rose the most in more than a week on speculation
that supplies are shrinking as demand climbs.  On ICE Futures U.S. in New York, cotton for July delivery
advanced 1 percent to 87.62 cents a pound.  Orange-juice futures for May delivery gained 0.7 percent to
$1.44 a pound.  Raw-sugar futures for July delivery climbed 0.3 percent to
17.84 cents a pound.  Cocoa futures for July delivery increased 1 percent to
$2,268 a ton.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery slid 1.4 percent
to $1.3715 a pound.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Wheat rose the most in a week as frigid weather in  North
America  raised the risk of damage to crops emerging from
dormancy and delays in spring planting.  On the Chicago Board of Trade, wheat futures for July
delivery jumped 2.3 percent to $7.195 a bushel, the biggest gain
since April 3.  Corn futures for July delivery rose 1.2 percent to $6.4125
a bushel.  Soybean futures for July delivery climbed 0.8 percent to
$13.7925 a bushel.  LIVESTOCK  Hogs rose, snapping a three-day slump, on speculation that
consumers will buy pork instead of pricier beef for outdoor
grilling.  On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, hog futures for June
settlement rose 0.5 percent to 89.9 cents a pound. The price, up
0.2 percent this week, has gained 4.9 percent in 2013.  Cattle futures for June delivery rose 0.1 percent to
$1.2075 a pound. The price has dropped 8.7 percent this year.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement dropped 0.6
percent to $1.40925 a pound.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Patrick McKiernan in  New York  at 
 pmckiernan@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
